        <title>On Writing Littered with ****ing Distractions</title>
        <published>2025-07-08T00:00:00+00:00</published>
        <updated>2025-07-08T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
        <author>
            <name>Khalid Hourani</name>
        </author>
        <link rel="alternate" href="https://khalid-salad.github.io/blog/distractions/" type="text/html"/>
        <id>https://khalid-salad.github.io/blog/distractions/</id>
        
            <content type="html">&lt;div class=&quot;admonition danger&quot;&gt;
    &lt;div class=&quot;admonition-icon admonition-icon-danger&quot;&gt;&lt;&#x2F;div&gt;
    &lt;div class=&quot;admonition-content&quot;&gt;
        &lt;strong class=&quot;admonition-title&quot;&gt;Curse Words&lt;&#x2F;strong&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;I will censor all the cursewords for now. I will try and find a toggle.&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;

    &lt;&#x2F;div&gt;
&lt;&#x2F;div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;One of the worst things about reading stuff from the internet is this expectation that, because you are probably reading this
in a web browser, it is cool to add stupid distractions like footnotes&lt;sup class=&quot;footnote-reference&quot; id=&quot;fr-distraction 1-1&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;#fn-distraction 1&quot;&gt;1&lt;&#x2F;a&gt;&lt;&#x2F;sup&gt; and &lt;a class=&quot;external&quot; href=&quot;https:&#x2F;&#x2F;www.wikipedia.org&#x2F;&quot;&gt;urls to unrelated bull****&lt;&#x2F;a&gt;.&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
&lt;aside &gt;
    &lt;p&gt;Did you know that the modern web is a great way to train your neck muscles?&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;

&lt;&#x2F;aside&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Notice, for example, that simply &lt;a class=&quot;external&quot; href=&quot;https:www.example.com&quot;&gt;linking to something&lt;&#x2F;a&gt; gives an unintended emphasis. At best,
this is distracting, but in many cases it changes the tone of the text.&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
&lt;aside data-position=&quot;right&quot;&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;You might have thought “the next paragraph will continue the topic being discussed”, but you would be wrong. The current
best practice is to distract your readers so much that they can’t follow your writing, then have them eviscerate you in
your evaluations and on ratemyprofessors.&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;

&lt;&#x2F;aside&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Similarly, the mere presence of a footnote can be distracting. For example, try and read the rest of this paragraph, but
disregard the upcoming footnote. I am not a big fan of Lorem Ipsum, because it just makes me feel insecure about the
fact that the only Latin I know is “post hoc ergo propter hoc”&lt;sup class=&quot;footnote-reference&quot; id=&quot;fr-distraction 2-1&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;#fn-distraction 2&quot;&gt;2&lt;&#x2F;a&gt;&lt;&#x2F;sup&gt; which roughly translates to “I studied
Spanish in high school.”&lt;sup class=&quot;footnote-reference&quot; id=&quot;fr-less distracting-1&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;#fn-less distracting&quot;&gt;3&lt;&#x2F;a&gt;&lt;&#x2F;sup&gt;&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;With that in mind, I approach my writing with:&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;A considerate approach to distractions. If the material you are serving is meant to be read, then it should, disregarding markup, be mostly plaintext.&lt;&#x2F;li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;A commitment to accessibility. The tabi theme used for this site is accessible. Currently, math and diagrams are rendered clientside using KaTeX and Mermaid. I hope to eventually have everything rendered serverside (with something like MathJax, which has a reputation for accessibility). The ideal would be to have the website fully functional with no JavaScript.&lt;&#x2F;li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Respect for the reader. External links will be kept to a minimum and clearly indicated (for example, here is an
external link to Daniel Podgorski’s excellent &lt;a class=&quot;external&quot; href=&quot;https:&#x2F;&#x2F;thegemsbok.com&#x2F;art-reviews-and-articles&#x2F;dark-souls-from-software-existentialism-philosophy&#x2F;&quot;&gt;Unchosen Undead: A Thorough Existentialist Philosophical Analysis of FromSoftware’s Original Dark Souls&lt;&#x2F;a&gt;).&lt;&#x2F;li&gt;
&lt;&#x2F;ol&gt;
&lt;footer class=&quot;footnotes&quot;&gt;
&lt;ol class=&quot;footnotes-list&quot;&gt;
&lt;li id=&quot;fn-distraction 1&quot;&gt;
&lt;p&gt;see how this **** interrupts your flow while reading? &lt;a href=&quot;#fr-distraction 1-1&quot;&gt;↩&lt;&#x2F;a&gt;&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
&lt;&#x2F;li&gt;
&lt;li id=&quot;fn-distraction 2&quot;&gt;
&lt;p&gt;ok i also know the initials QED &lt;a href=&quot;#fr-distraction 2-1&quot;&gt;↩&lt;&#x2F;a&gt;&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
&lt;&#x2F;li&gt;
&lt;li id=&quot;fn-less distracting&quot;&gt;
&lt;p&gt;this one, at the end of the paragraph, is noticeably less distracting. There is an art to
this, but i am not a good writer &lt;a href=&quot;#fr-less distracting-1&quot;&gt;↩&lt;&#x2F;a&gt;&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
&lt;&#x2F;li&gt;
&lt;&#x2F;ol&gt;
&lt;&#x2F;footer&gt;
</content>
        <summary type="html">My Commitment to Not Writing like ****</summary>
        </entry><entry xml:lang="en">
        <title>How to Describe an Algorithm</title>
        <published>2025-07-08T00:00:00+00:00</published>
        <updated>2025-07-08T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
        <author>
            <name>Khalid Hourani</name>
        </author>
        <link rel="alternate" href="https://khalid-salad.github.io/blog/how-to-explain-an-algorithm/" type="text/html"/>
        <id>https://khalid-salad.github.io/blog/how-to-explain-an-algorithm/</id>
        
            <content type="html">&lt;h1 id=&quot;introduction&quot;&gt;Introduction&lt;&#x2F;h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;How many times have you explained an algorithm like this, or at least seen such an explanation?&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
&lt;pre data-name=&quot;dog**** quality pseudocode to sort array arr of length n&quot; class=&quot;z-code&quot;&gt;&lt;code data-name=&quot;dog**** quality pseudocode to sort array arr of length n&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;z-text z-plain&quot;&gt;for i in 0..n:
&lt;&#x2F;span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;z-text z-plain&quot;&gt;  for j in i+1..n:
&lt;&#x2F;span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;z-text z-plain&quot;&gt;    if arr[j] &amp;lt; arr[i]:
&lt;&#x2F;span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;z-text z-plain&quot;&gt;      swap arr[i] and arr[j]
&lt;&#x2F;span&gt;&lt;&#x2F;code&gt;&lt;&#x2F;pre&gt;
</content>
        <summary type="html">Explaining an algorithm correctly and in a way that is digestible is hard. This page provides tips.</summary>
